"circa 1304":"okolo 1304","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","Bostock, Cheshire, England":"Bostock, Cheshire, Anglie"},"da":{"circa 1304–1328":"omkring 1304–1328","1285–1325":"1285–1325","1304–1328":"1304–1328","–Male":"Afdød","–1374":"–1374","1270–1312":"1270–1312","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1312":"1312","1320":"1320","24 April 1312":"24. april 1312","1374":"1374","1285":"1285","circa 1304":"omkring 1304","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","Bostock, Cheshire, England":"Bostock, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"circa 1304–1328":"circa 1304–1328","1285–1325":"1285–1325","1304–1328":"1304–1328","–Male":"Overleden","–1374":"–1374","1270–1312":"1270–1312","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1312":"1312","1320":"1320","24 April 1312":"24 april 1312","1374":"1374","1285":"1285","circa 1304":"circa 1304","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","Bostock, Cheshire, England":"Bostock, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"circa 1304–1328":"about 1304–1328","1285–1325":"1285–1325","1304–1328":"1304–1328","–Male":"Deceased","–1374":"–1374","1270–1312":"1270–1312","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1312":"1312","1320":"1320","24 April 1312":"24 April 1312","1374":"1374","1285":"1285","circa 1304":"about 1304","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","Bostock, Cheshire, England":"Bostock, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vernon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Vernon in Eure, France, named from the Gaulish element <i>ver(n)</i> ‘alder’ + the Gallo-Roman locative suffix <i>-o</i> (genitive <i>-ōnis</i>).","French: habitational name from the same place as in 1 above or from any of several other places in France with the same name and etymology."],"variants":[{"name":"Varnon","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Northamptonshire): variant of   Vernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thor","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."]}]},{"name":"Margerie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Margary  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margary","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret or Margerie Vernon was born about 1304, her father, Ralph de Vernon, was 36 and her mother, Margaret St Pierre, was 46. She had at least 2 sons with John de Whitmore. She died in 1328, at the age of 25."},"et":{"circa 1304–1328":"umbes 1304–1328","1285–1325":"1285–1325","1304–1328":"1304–1328","–Male":"Surnud","–1374":"–1374","1270–1312":"1270–1312","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1312":"1312","1320":"1320","24 April 1312":"24. aprill 1312","1374":"1374","1285":"1285","circa 1304":"umbes 1304","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1328":"1328